@node intro "Introduction"
@{jcenter} @{"Main" link main} Introduction @{"Requirements" link reqs} @{"Usage" link usage} @{"Technicalities" link geekstuff} @{"Conversions" link convert} @{"About Me" link about}


@{jcenter}@{b}The Story@{ub}


@{jleft}	In 2009, my Amiga 1200 was much as any other. A CPU upgrade, some memory, 10Mbps card in the PCMCIA slot, and so on. Compeletely cool for fun and games, as well as some @{i}extremely@{ui} simple work, it was fine. However, my first semester of tech school was upon me, and I needed something with a bit more horsepower to handle the demands of a computer course for A+ certification. Among the requirements were the ability to use CD-ROMs, a USB thumb-drive for saving/loading homework, and a browser that won't choke on the (required for homework) javascript loaded school websites.


@{jcenter}@{b}The Upgrade@{ub}


@{jleft}	So instead of doing what any reasonable student would have done, and purchase a brand new multi-core machine with more memory than all the Amiga games I play combined will ever use (along with an operating system that will consistantly use almost all of this huge heap of memory), with the lastest this that and the other "obsolete in a year" stuff, I decided to tower my Amiga (which cost about twice as much, but was @{b}MUCH@{ub} more entertaining). The tower allowed me access to the Mediator card, with 24bit graphics vie P96, soundblaster support (which I still don't use much), and 100mbps ethernet. Also, I got a SubWay USB card, which worked @{b}@{i}MUCH@{ui}@{ub} better than I ever thought it would. Of all the USB stuff I had lying about for my (dying) Compaq Presario w/ WinXP (BLECH!), only 2 or 3 things didn't work. Among the things that DID work, was my trusty Sony Clié, which was able to connect as either a flashdrive (with the transfer program on the Clié), or launch a script on the Amiga when Hotsync was engaged. The software included programs to transfer files back and forth via hotsync, allowing a complete backup of my Clié onto my 1200.


@{jcenter}@{b}The inspiration@{ub}


@{jleft}	My Clié was as integral part of my student life, helping me take notes, set homework reminders, play Tetris whilst the instructor was lecturing on about something s/he assumed was interesting, and so on. The problem was, I could write all this stuff into my PDA, and copy it all to the Amiga, but it was all saved as .pdb files. These .pdb files won't load into anything other than a HEX editor, and some other PDA applications written for the Amiga. (Spitfire is a good one, but it lacks the "integration" that I was after) I was constantly tapping away at my Clié, looking at my schedule so I could enter it into Limpidclock, and doing the same for whatever contacts I had put into my PDA address book with YAM. Spitfire had an option to import the address book, and save it as a .csv file, while YAM has the ability to import the same, but the fields were all wrong. I was originally going to whip up a quick and dirty C proggy to re-arrange the spitfire files fields for YAM compatibility, but figured I might as well take care of all my .pdb woes at once. This is when I started working on PDAconvert, which was designed to be modular enough to handle most .pdb files.


@{jcenter}@{b}The setback(s)@{ub}


@{jleft}	Unfortunately, between school, work, and my 2 year old daughter, this kinda got put on the back burner for awhile. Plus, there were alot of new programming concepts a beginner like myself needed to learn, and I was busy "learning" other stuff. (How to edit windows registry, how to change BIOS settings, how a college-level course can get away with teaching really basic stuff like that, etc...). Also, there was the .PDB file themselves. Looking at a HEX editor, I could see the plaintext stuff easily, but the other data made no sense (PDB's are kinda weird in some ways). Fortunately, the .pdb format is pretty well documented, and I was able to track down what meant what. However there are various technicalities that kept me from achieving any success for a long time. (see @{"here" link geekstuff} for details) As well as sytem crashes, inexperience with programming, listening to the Barney theme song (the 2 yo. liked to watch TV in my office....), and several other annoyances I left it alone for a long time.


@{jcenter}@{b}The rebound@{ub}


@{jleft}	Now, in 2010, I'm at it again with school, and have finally gotten fed up with the previously mentioned problems with double-entering everything. Also, I've been tinkering with programs for awhile now, and am @{i}FINALLY@{ui} getting ahead on this little project. After digging up my old source code, I figured I'd just re-write it from the beginning. And this (such as it is) is the result.


@{jcenter} @{"Main" link main} Introduction @{"Requirements" link reqs} @{"Usage" link usage} @{"Technicalities" link geekstuff} @{"Conversions" link convert} @{"About Me" link about}


@endnode

@node reqs "Requirements"
@{jcenter} @{"Main" link main} @{"Introduction" link intro} Requirements @{"Usage" link usage} @{"Technicalities" link geekstuff} @{"Conversions" link convert} @{"About Me" link about}


@{b}System Requirements:@{ub}


@{jright}An Amiga! :D (Or an emulator, I suppose)


CPU/Memory: 68000 or better, 1MB RAM or more.


OS: Tested on AOS3.9, probably 2.x will work fine, possibly even 1.3.


Files: any supported PalmOS .pdb file. (Eg. datebookdb.pdb)


@{i}Recommended@{ui}


A PalmOS PDA (rather pointless to run this without one)


USB support (Most PDA's connect this way)


@{jleft}	The program doesn't require anything particularly exotic. (Except, of course, for an Amiga and a PalmOS PDA) It was developed on an Amiga 1200T 060 50Mhz w/ 192MB RAM, and the executable shouldn't occupy more than 80 Kb (I've not finished writing it at this point, so that IS just a guess). The conversion files should be pretty small, too, so I wouldn't expect this to exceed the size of a DD Amiga floppy disk.  I'll optimize for 68000 and 68020, though I don't see much advantage for going above 020 with what I'm doing. I'll do 68000 as well, in case ANAIS can address a PDA.


	As for memory, I don't think any more than 1MB should be needed for most files. If you have a 10MB PDB file, then you'll need at least that much RAM. Most PDB files are rather compact, though. (The OS was designed to squeeze as much "heap ram" out of a handheld as possible).


	Of course, you'll need a PalmOS PDB file, which means some way of getting it into your Amiga (or emulator, though I can't imagine why you would do that). Obviously, if you don't have USB support, you're going to run into problems with 90% of the PDA's out there. I believe there is a 9-pin com port pinout for Palm PDA's, but I'm unsure as to the wiring, or commercial availability of these cables. For commercial cables, you will almost certainly need a 25-9 pin adapter, otherwise if you're a pretty good solder-jockey, and find the pinout, you could just wire it straight to a 25-pin connector.


	And lastly, you need to avoid being shy of CLI programs. :) I didn't put a GUI in this thing, and its unlikely I will. (I may change my mind, though) Its originally designed for inclusion in AmigaDOS scripts, so a GUI would be rather pointless.


@{jcenter} @{"Main" link main} @{"Introduction" link intro} Requirements @{"Usage" link usage} @{"Technicalities" link geekstuff} @{"Conversions" link convert} @{"About Me" link about}


@endnode

@node usage "Usage"
@{jcenter} @{"Main" link main} @{"Introduction" link intro} @{"Requirements" link reqs} Usage @{"Technicalities" link geekstuff} @{"Conversions" link convert} @{"About Me" link about}


@{jleft} PDAconvert is a CLI application, with no GUI. Its best used in a script that launches during a hotsync operation, in order to convert various files automatically. I use a SubWay USB card with the included PDAtransfer program to download the .pdb files from the PDA, and add PDAconvert commands after the download. Poseidon can launches this script on a hotsync command.

@{jcenter}@{b}CLI template@{ub}

@{jleft}	pdaconvert @{b}-i@{ub}/s @{b}-o@{ub}/s @{b}-c@{ub}/s @{b}-rg@{ub}/s @{b}-rh@{ub}/s
	

@{jcenter}@{i}example:@{ui}

@{jleft}PDAconvert @{b}-i@{ub} @{u}spitfire:users/fred/system/memodb.pdb@{uu} @{b}-o@{ub} @{u}documents:AmigaGuides/PDA_Memos.guide@{uu} @{b}-c@{ub} @{u}guide@{uu} @{b}-rg@{ub} @{u}ram:debugoutput.guide@{uu}



@{jcenter}@{b}Description of options@{ub}


@{jleft}	@{b}-i@{ub} \"@{u}Input file@{uu}\": The file you want to load.


	@{b}-o@{ub} \"@{u}Output file@{uu}\": Name of the file to save to.


	@{b}-c@{ub} \"@{u}Output format@{uu}\": Format to convert file to. (Eg. guide, html, doc, etc...)


	@{b}-rg@{ub} \"@{u}Output file@{uu}\": Quick and dirty Amigaguide file showing PDB file HEX/ASCII.

		(more info @{"Here" link dbfiles})


	@{b}-rh@{ub} \"@{u}Output file@{uu}\": Quick and dirty HTML file showing PDB file HEX/ASCII data.

		(more info @{"Here" link dbfiles})


@{jcenter} @{"Main" link main} @{"Introduction" link intro} @{"Requirements" link reqs} Usage @{"Technicalities" link geekstuff} @{"Conversions" link convert} @{"About Me" link about}


@endnode

@node geekstuff "Technical issues for geeks"
@{jcenter} @{"Main" link main} @{"Introduction" link intro} @{"Requirements" link reqs} @{"Usage" link usage} Technicalities @{"Conversions" link convert} @{"About Me" link about}


@{b}Technical issues@{ub}


@{i}Caution! excessive use of geek-speak!@{ui}


@{jleft}	While writing this, there were several problems that arose. My lack of experience not being the least, some more specific issues like bit-encoded attributes, weird data structures, misuse of the malloc() command resulting in pdaconvert dumping stuff into sytsem memory, etc.... This is a list of the problems, in order of most to least annoying. (Mostly because thats the order in which I remember them....)


@{jcenter}@{u}Bit-encoded attributes@{uu}


@{jleft}	All that means is that PalmOS (Like most other OS's, including the Amiga) uses bits to switch on and off various attributes. Which bits mean what are well documented, and some files for PalmOS make for easy reverse-engineering if they weren't. The problem that arose is me being a complete beginner at this sort of programming. Using gcc version 2.95.3 (I know its probably an old version, but it works) and regular C (NOT C++), I had to figure out how to access these "bits". Unfortunately, the smallest form of data possible to address is a byte, or in the case of C, and unsigned char. PalmOS uses both a 16-bit integer and an 8-bit integer to store attributes. The database itself uses a 16 bit, allowing for 16 different attributes. The records in the database only get 8 attributes (4 of which are hardly ever used, anyway). My first idea was to read the attributes as 8-bit integers, and assign a data array to decode which combination of attributes the number represents. (I would need 2 unsigned chars for the database, and 1 for each record) This turned out to be a @{b}REALLY STUPID IDEA@{ub}, as the math reveals each unsigned char results in 256 combinations of attributes. There might be a (very) slight speed increase in doing things this way, but would result each database requiring at least 768 bytes for the attributes (256*3, 3= 2 for the database, and 1 for the records). While this isn't a whole lot of memory, (less than a kilobyte) its quite the increase from whats needed when the attributes themselves only consume 3 bytes, assuming a database with 1 record. 


	My next idea was to bitshift the integer to the left in a loop, and determine if its a negative or positive value after reading it as a signed char, which seems to be a pretty standard way of handling things for big-endian systems. (Motorola CPU's eg: 680x0, ppc, ARM are big-endian, PalmOS devices typically use 68000 or ARM CPU's, and the Amiga, of course, uses 680x0 or PPC, unless you're an AROS fan.) While this would have probably worked if I had pursued it further, the endian-specific nature of this and the possibility of porting this to AROS later (x86 CPU's are little-endian, would require a re-write of the code) lead me to pursue a 3rd option (which will probably still need re-writing for AROS systems anyway)


	What I finally settled on was using a loop that would run 2 to the power of the counting variable as an AND bitmask. If the result was 0, the binary digit specified by the counting variable was 0. If it was something else, it was 1. 2^4=16, 16 in binary is 0001000 for 8-bit itegers. If the attribute contains a 1 in the 4th digit, the AND operation will return a 16, which isn't 0. If the 4th digits a 0, the operation will return a 0. Because the only thing that can result in 1&1=1 is the 4th digit, the other 7 (or 15 depending on bitwidth) digits will be ignored. (0&1=0, 0&0=0, 1&1=1) This is another typical way of doing things, and it worked. I just dumped the results into an array, and set up a nomenclature array to read back the values "meaning" when scanned.


@{jcenter}@{u}Non-Standard date method@{uu}


@{jleft}	OK. Every computer I've ever encountered measures time. And it mesures time in seconds elapsed since January 1st, 1970. That is, every computer I've encountered until I got a PDA. I don't know if one of the PalmOS developers grandparents died on January 1st 1904, or perhaps a great uncle, or what the hell happened on January 1st 1904. But for some reason, PalmOS measures the date in seconds elapsed from this date. While the rest of the computing world uses 1970, Palm had some infatuation that resulted in my datestamps being 66 years off. (Did you know there are 2,082,844,800 seconds between January 1st, 1904 and January 1st, 1970? Until writing this, I didn't know, nor care....) Anyway, by simply adjusting PalmOS time by 2,082,844,800 seconds, this problem was solved. The only thing that remains.... WHY THE #$%&*%^!!!! 1904????? (I could understand the need to address dates before 1970, but thats why the usual time is signed....)


@{jcenter}@{u}24 bit integers!?!?!@{uu}


@{jleft}	This just doesn't fit into C very well. In C, I can use a char (8-bit), a short (16-bit), or an int (32-bit). If I need more than that, I can do ulong, double or whatever. But in the record headers in a pdb file, the records ID number is a 24-bit integer. There are 64 bits total in the thing. The first 32 bits are, of course, a 32-bit integer, and simply shows the offset for the record information. The last 24(?!?!?!) bits are the records ID number. OK, 32+24=56 bits. Thats 8 less than the 64 bits in the header. The other 8-bits are the records attributes, which in light of cramming as much stuff into a record as possible, makes sense. Granted, if you have 16,777,217 records, you're out of id numbers, but unless you're dumping the contents of every phone number in the United States into your datebook, thats still alot of record space. The thing is, I kept trying to dump a 24-bit integer into a 32-bit variable. For some reason completely unknown to me at the time (Turns out I needed to force the data to unsigned), I was getting weird results. Anyway, its fixed now. I just manually added the individual chars together. (data[positon]*65536+data[position+1]*256+data[position+2]). Anyway, this is a really minor annoyance in hindsight.


@{jcenter}@{u}Using Malloc() with insufficient caffeine@{uu}


@{jleft}	This little problem shows how much of a beginner I am... The Malloc() command. For those who don't know, Malloc stands for memory allocation, and is used to assign memory to a "pointer". This pointer (usually defined as something like char *unknown_length; for a bunch of 8-bit variables, how many of which you don't know) is simply a memory location where anything you assign to it will be stored. If you assign something larger than the allocated memory, the compiler will only catch it if its a static length. For example if char *string; is 4 bytes long, and you try dumping a constant you defined as 5 bits long into it, a good compiler will complain, but if you dump an unknown into it, perhaps the result of a for loop, the program will compile, and the system will happily dump data to the indicated location until it overwrites some critical system memory location, in which case you crash and burn. This is what things like protected memory are designed to prevent, and why the Amiga has Enforcer, among a slew of other MMU (the 68k memory protection component) applications. Unfortunately, the Amiga's OS doesn't support MMU stuff without such 3rd party options, and these apps can slow your system down, so they're typically only used for debugging. For some reason or another, these MMU tools crash my system completely, even though virtually everything else that uses the MMU works fine. (Virtual memory, Macintosh emulation, Kickstart remappers, etc...) So by not using them, I didn't realize all my blahblah=malloc(whatever) commands should have read blahblah=malloc(whatever@{b}+1@{ub}), resulting in the resulting executable scattering data randomly throughout my memory like buckshot. And like anything hit with buckshot, it randomly overwrote something critical, and I found myself cussing at a blinking red box...... After adding the +1 to all my malloc statements, this no longer was a problem.


@{jcenter} @{"Main" link main} @{"Introduction" link intro} @{"Requirements" link reqs} @{"Usage" link usage} Technicalities @{"Conversions" link convert} @{"About Me" link about}


@endnode

@node convert "Conversion method and how-to"
@{jcenter} @{"Main" link main} @{"Introduction" link intro} @{"Requirements" link reqs} @{"Usage" link usage} @{"Technicalities" link geekstuff} Conversions @{"About Me" link about}


@{b}How the conversions work:@{ub}

@{jleft}	PDAconvert is a really simple program. It just organizes PalmOS's PDB database fields into variables, and provides them as output for a (very) basic markup/scripting language. I did things this way because while converting the address book, memo pad, datebook, and to-do applications to YAM contacts, amigaguide, and limpidclock reminder files would be great, the number of different applications and database files available for PalmOS is huge. I don't stand a snowballs chance in hell of being able to code all of 'em. By using a script to do it, somebody using a really obscure database can write their own conversions for it. Also, you can add Amiga program support the same way, in case you use Contact Manager, SimpleMail, or some other program for you contacts.


	The program first loads @{u}env:pdaconvert@{uu} to get its settings. Then, it loads the pdb file into memory, and identifies it. After identification, it loads the appropriate conversion script, and looks up the requested file format (html, guide, pdf, whatever). Then it executes the script for that format, or returns an error if it isn't found. Then it write any requested \"raw\" data to the appropriate files. And then terminates with a general rundown of what happened.


	The conversion information is stored in a text file, located in the conversions directory. The program looks these files in the path noted by @{u}env:pdaconvert@{uu}, otherwise it will look in the current directory in @{u}conversions/@{uu}. I mention the current directory, because if you install PDAconvert into @{U}C:@{UU}, it won't look in C: for the conversions. It will look in whatever directory you happen to be in, and will happily tell you it doesn't know what file you're looking at. Anyway, copying the conversions directory to @{u}s:pdaconversions/@{uu}, and typing @{b}SetEnv PDAconvert s:pdaconversions/ save@{ub} will avoid this problem. I might do something more elaborate than this in the future, though.


	The conversions directory contains files named by a .pdb databases type/creator string. If you use the @{b}-rg@{ub} or @{b}-rh@{ub} options, the resulting output will show you the strings. For example, MemoDB.pdb is PalmOS's Memo book file, and has a type/creator id of DATA/memo. @{u}conversions/data.memo@{uu} is the file PDAconvert will look for when decoding MemoDB.pdb.

	
	The file is separated by tags. Aside from a few names reserved for the program, these name the \"format\" the containing script produces. These tags are contained in \{\} brackets (E.G. \{pdf\} will run when @{b}-c@{ub} @{u}pdf@{uu} is called).

	

@{jcenter}@{b}PDAconvert specific tags@{ub}


\"@{u}\{info\}@{uu}\"


@{jleft}	This contains plain-text information about the type of pdb file the conversion is for. More accurately, it's for the program that generates that type of database. This area only contains 4 lines, organized like this:

Description	(Simple description of the database)

Author		(The author or company who wrote the program for the database)

E-mail		(Contact e-mail for that programs support, or authors E-mail.)

			@{B}ASK PERMISSION BEFORE PUTTING ANYTHING HERE!!!@{UB}

Website		(The softwares website URL, if any)

	If any of these entries don't apply, just leave an empty line. Or N/A it if it makes you feel better.


@{jcenter}@{b}Conversion tags@{ub}

@{jleft}	The other tags are simply scripted instructions. The Scripting is simple enough, its a markup style in that any text in the area will be passed through to the final output, unless preceeded by an escape character.


@{jcenter}@{u}Escape Characters@{uu}


@{jleft}	@{b}#@{ub}	This writes a @{"variable" link variables}.

	@{b}(@{ub}	This starts a @{"loop" link loop}, terminated by @{b})@{ub}.


@{jcenter} @{"Main" link main} @{"Introduction" link intro} @{"Requirements" link reqs} @{"Usage" link usage} @{"Technicalities" link geekstuff} Conversions @{"About Me" link about}


@endnode

@node about "About me"
