@node variables "PDAconverts Variables"

@{jcenter} @{"Main" link main} @{"Introduction" link intro} @{"Requirements" link reqs} @{"Usage" link usage} @{"Technicalities" link geekstuff} @{"Conversions" link convert} @{"About Me" link about}

@{u}Quick Reference@{uu}

@{"[] Range values" link ranges} @{"() Loop values" link loop} @{b}# variable values@{ub}


@{b}Variables@{ub}


@{jleft}	These are the variable that are available when using the '@{b}#@{ub}' character in a script.

	@{b}#@{ub}	Writes a @{b}#@{ub} character.

	@{b}(@{ub}	Writes a @{b}(@{ub} character.

	@{b}v@{ub}	PDAconverts $VER: version information.

	@{b}A@{ub} @{i}n@{ui}	Database Attribute string #@{i}n@{ui}. (Hexidecimal, 0-F)

	@{b}a@{ub} @{i}n@{ui}	Record Attribute String #@{i}n@{ui}.	

	@{b}T@{ub} @{i}n@{ui}	Database Attribute # @{i}n@{ui}. (1=on, 0=off, Hexidecimal, 0-F)

	@{b}V@{ub}	Database Version #. (Usually a 0)

	@{b}P@{ub}	Database Type.

	@{b}p@{ub}	Database Creator.

	@{b}I@{ub}	Database ID #.

	@{b}c@{ub}	Database creation date.

	@{b}m@{ub}	Database last modification date.

	@{b}b@{ub}	Database last backup date.

	@{b}C@{ub} @{i}n@{ui}	Category #@{i}n@{ui}.

	@{b}q@{ub}	Number of records in database.

	@{b}Q@{ub}	Length of database file (On computer).

	@{b}t@{ub} @{i}n@{ui}	Current records attribute (1=on, 0=off)

	@{b}s@{ub}	Current records start offset.

	@{b}S@{ub}	Current records end offset.

	@{b}r@{ub}	Current records record ID #.

	@{b}F@{ub}	Database types information (from \{info\} tag).

	@{b}H@{ub}	Database author information (from \{info\} tag).

	@{b}W@{ub}	Database website information (from \{info\} tag).

	@{b}E@{ub}	Database Email information (from \{info\} tag).

	@{b}A@{ub}	Database Appinfo ID.

	@{b}N@{ub}	The PDB files name. (NOT the filename, the name in the header)

	@{b}R@{ub}	The current record number. (Will always be 0 unless in a @{"loop" link loop})

	@{b}[@{ub}	Writes a @{"range" link ranges} of data, terminated by a @{b}]@{ub} character.


@endnode


@node ranges "Range values"

@{jcenter} @{"Main" link main} @{"Introduction" link intro} @{"Requirements" link reqs} @{"Usage" link usage} @{"Technicalities" link geekstuff} @{"Conversions" link convert} @{"About Me" link about}

@{u}Quick Reference@{uu}

@{b}[] Range values@{ub} @{"() Loop values" link loop} @{"# variable values" link variables}


@{b}Range values@{ub}

@{jleft}
	
	Ranges are defined by @{b}#[@{ub}@{u}start value@{uu}@{b},@{ub}@{u}end value@{uu}@{b}]@{ub}, and are for copying a sequential series of data from the .pdb file to the output file. All range values are offsets from the beginning of the current record (which will always be record 0 if outside a @{"loop" link loop}). Be careful when assigning static numbers here, as exceeding the length of the record could cause problems. Exceeding the .pdb files length @{i}will@{ui} cause problems.

		@{b}Number@{ub}	Start of the range of data in decimal offset.

			0 would be 1st byte of the record.


		@{b}e@{ub}	The first carraige return after the beginning of a range.

			Can only be used to end a range.


		@{b}E@{ub}	The end of the record.

			Again only to be used to end a range.

		@{b}]@{ub}	Terminates the range tag.


@{jcenter} @{"Main" link main} @{"Introduction" link intro} @{"Requirements" link reqs} @{"Usage" link usage} @{"Technicalities" link geekstuff} @{"Conversions" link convert} @{"About Me" link about}

@endnode

@node loop "Loop usage"

@{jcenter} @{"Main" link main} @{"Introduction" link intro} @{"Requirements" link reqs} @{"Usage" link usage} @{"Technicalities" link geekstuff} @{"Conversions" link convert} @{"About Me" link about}

@{u}Quick Reference@{uu}

@{"[] Range values@" link ranges} @{b}Loop Values@{ub} @{"# variable values" link variables}


@{b}Loop usage@{ub}

@{jleft}	A loop is just that. It cycles from one value to the end value, repeating everything in between. Loops start with a @{b}(@{ub}, and end with @{b})@{ub}. As of now, the only loops are from the first record to the last record in a .pdb file. Typically, you will extract the "index" of a file with one loop, and use a second for the actual content (common for files that \"hyperlink\", like HTML or AmigaGuide), but this isn't always the case. This documentation is here for future expansion, as more options are planned.

		@{b}(@{ub}	Begin loop.

		@{b})@{ub}	End loop.
@endnode

@node dbfiles "Raw output files"

@{jcenter} @{"Main" link main} @{"Introduction" link intro} @{"Requirements" link reqs} @{"Usage" link usage} @{"Technicalities" link geekstuff} @{"Conversions" link convert} @{"About Me" link about}

@{b}Raw output files@{ub}


@{jleft}	This is an option I originally used for debugging purposes, though it can be useful for writing @{"conversion scripts" link convert} as well. It dumps the .pdb header into an index node or file (Amigaguide or HTML depending), and links the records from there.


	It also displays the attributes of both the header and the individual records, and has the option of listing only those records that have a particular attribute set (useful for determining what some more exotic programs use the \"reserved\" attribute for).


	The attributes are listed by name, and clicking on one (if active) will show a list of all records that have that attribute set. The 4 \"reserved\" attributes in the records usually refer to the category that record belongs to, and is actually a 4-bit integer (0-15, try adding a 17th category in memopad and see what happens).


	The records themselves are displayed in both ASCII (or a \"stub\" character for unreadable bytes), and hexidecimal. This saves you the trouble of digging up a hex editor. Also, the entire .pdb file is exported in dual ASCII//HEX as well.


